# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grpc-go-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:grpc-go-lib/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] gRPC uses HTTP/2 for transport, Protocol Buffers as the interface description language, and provides features such as authentication, bidirectional streaming and flow control, blocking or nonblocking bindings, and cancellation and timeouts.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] The most common usage scenarios include connecting services in a microservices style architecture, or connecting mobile device clients to backend services.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] gRPC's use of HTTP trailers makes it impossible to implement a gRPC client in a browser, instead requiring a proxy.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] From about 2001, Google created a general-purpose RPC infrastructure called Stubby to connect the large number of microservices running within and across its data centers.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] In March 2015, Google decided to build the next version of Stubby and make it open source.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] gRPC supports the usage of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and token-based authentication.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] Connection to Google services must use TLS.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] There are two types of credentials: channel credentials and call credentials.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] For token-based authorization, gRPC provides Server Interceptor and a Client Interceptor.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] gRPC uses Protocol Buffers to encode data.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] Protocol buffers provide a serialization format and an interface definition language.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] Some of the software tools used for testing gRPC implementations include Postman, ezy, Insomnia, and Step CI.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] Many organizations use gRPC, including Uber, Square, Netflix, IBM, CoreOS, Docker, CockroachDB, Arista Networks, Cisco, Juniper Networks, Spotify, Zalando, Dropbox, and Google as the original developer.
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] The open source project u-bmc uses gRPC to replace Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
[src:grpc-go-lib/grpc] On 8 January 2019, Dropbox announced that the next version of "Courier", their RPC framework at the core of their service-oriented architecture (SOA), would be migrated to be based on gRPC, primarily because it aligned well with their existing custom RPC frameworks.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:grpc-go-lib/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:grpc-go-lib/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:grpc-go-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:grpc-go-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:grpc-go-lib/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:grpc-go-lib/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:grpc-go-lib/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:grpc-go-lib/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
